<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-306-926  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 306 926.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  April 2 1990 v12 n14 p41(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Virus stories can sell papers, but may contain a Trojan horse.andO;(publicity surrounding computer virus scares)(State of theIndustry) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Foster, Ed.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computer viruses represent a genuine threat to all computer users,but their destructive potential has been exaggerated by the media.andO;Stories predicting the fall of civilization through the imminentactivation of exotic viruses surface periodically because franticheadlines help sell daily newspapers.andP;  Almost all computer virusesfizzle out, destroying the credibility of actual virus threats andleaving users vulnerable because newspaper readers get theimpression that viruses need not be taken seriously.andP;  Peter S.andO;Tippett of FoundationWare Inc has developed a mathematical modelfor predicting how fast computer viruses will spread.andP;  Tippettpredicts that DOS viruses could become epidemic in less than fiveyears, and his paper has been endorsed by many respectableanalysts although not subjected to scientific validation.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer VirusesComputer CrimesData SecurityPublic Relations.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>